</td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Video question...</span><hr size=1> I'm running ME with an ATI Radeon 64MB DRR video card and Direct X 8.0, and it works fine.<br>
<br>
I don't think its the OS alone, the truth is, depending upon the motherboard, the Video Card, the OS, and the DX version, you may have issues.  Nothing is 100% fully compliant anymore, whether we're talking software, motherboards, drivers, API Definitions, or video cards.<br>
<br>
My only suggestion is to restore to what worked before.  IF that does not work, then you may want to build from the ground up, reinstalling the OS first, then the MotherBoard AGP drivers - downloaded from the manufacturer, then the video drivers, THEN DX.  I'd start with DX 7, see if it works, if it does, stop, if not, then go to DX 8.0 (not a), if not then 8.0a, etc.. <br>
<br>
DX is probably the most flakey of all the variables.  I have a Pentium CPU on an ASUS P5A (Socket 7) motherboard.  Asus is one of the best MB manufacturers going, and I never had any problems before, but when I installed a new NVidia Card, it puked.  I got new drivers from Nvidia, it still puked on any application open command.  I got new AGP drivers from ASUS, it still puked - after my deleting the Vid Card drivers first, installing the AGP driver and then reinstalling the vid card drivers and DX 8.0.  Finally, I blew off the OS, installed AGP drivers, installed vid drivers and installed DX 8.0, and now it works fine, EXCEPT for DOAC (dammit).  The point being, when you go monkeying with Dynamic Link Libraries (DLL's) in Windows OS, Windows does not monitor that change so that you can remove it, once its changed, your set, and ONLY reinstalling the OS to base OS reverts the DLL's to their original state.  <br>
<br>
My next step is to install DX 7.0 on my board.  If that works, then I'll assume that on an ASUS P5A, with an Nvidia Card, and the Build 1.63 of the AGP drivers, and DX 7.0, that DAOC works, and I'll assume nothing else.  The point is, its not JUST the OS, or the VC drivers, or DX that is the answer, it could be any or all  that need fixing, and what works on one MB may well not work on another.<br>
<br>
Happy Hunting!<br>
